Currently in `_path` source files, `?v=#{$fa-version}` is appended to all urls. I understand this is a really nice default for automatic caching scenarios. In my scenario though it's a pain, as we have versioning arranged in an html5 appcache manifest. We automatically build the appcache from filenames where there is no way to know which version is used causing the browser to not find the font file in its cache.

I'd love to have a directive `$fa-append-version = true/false` which toggles appending the version:

```
$fa-append-version defaults to true

@font-face {
  font-family: 'FontAwesome';
  @if $fa-append-version {
    src: url('#{$fa-font-path}/fontawesome-webfont.eot?v=#{$fa-version}');
  } @else {
    src: url('#{$fa-font-path}/fontawesome-webfont.eot');
  }
}
```

Thanks!

The function `compile_missing_pyc` currently tries to compile every single `.py` file it encounters on Python 2.x, and this can prevent packages that include syntactically invalid `.py` files for testing from functioning properly. 

For example, I created a `pylint` recipe (ContinuumIO/conda-recipes#32) and it works for Python 3 (because conda only uses `compile_missing_pyc` for Python 2), but it fails with Python 2 because the forced compilation of some invalid Python files. For code analysis tools like `pylint` it is important to have the ability to include test files that have invalid syntax.

Fixing this issue will likely require adding something to the `meta.yaml` file format that specifies the files that should be skipped, but I wasn't exactly sure how you would want to approach that (which is why this an issue and not a PR).

